        "date_qualifier_title": "",
        "date_qualifier_id": null,
        "artist_display": "Suzanne Duchamp\nFrench, 1889–1963",
        "place_of_origin": "France",
        description: "<p>Like many Dada works, those by Suzanne Duchamp weave painting, collage, and language together in complex ways. <em>Broken and Restored Multiplication</em> is filled with visual and verbal metaphors of disorder and breakage: at the center, a schematic Eiffel Tower is turned upside down; just below it, a modern cityscape is reflected in its mirror image. The phrases that run up and down along the surface of the picture further the idea of order upended: &quot;The mirror would shatter, the scaffolding would totter, the balloons would fly away, the stars would dim, etc.&quot; Such images and words seemed fitting for the artists who embraced Dada, a cultural movement that emerged in response to World War I.</p>\n",
        dimensions: "61 × 50 cm (24 × 19 11/16 in.)",
